@node Introduction "AquaSettings v1.0 Documentation"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
AquaSettings is meant to be used on the W command. You probably have lots
of commands that the users can configure different things with, for
example AutoSent, the filescanner, CF (conference flags) and of course the
internal W command. AquaSettings will show a menu of all these commands,
something like this:

[ 1] Basic settings
[ 2] Conference flags
[ 3] AutoSent
[ 4] Filescan options
etc.

When you select one of these, that command is executed and then the menu
is shown again, until you quit with a single <Enter>. Unfortunately, if
you're running SigmaExpress or AmiExpress 2.xx and you choose "[ 1] Basic
settings" (which is the internal W command), you won't be taken back to
the menu. That "bug" is because of a limitation in S!X and /X 2.xx that
doesn't let you run an internal command (with the same name as a door)
without quitting the door. In /X 3.0+ there is a way around this (see
@{"installation" Link Installation} section).

The door can take a command number as argument. For example if you start
the door by typing 'W 3', AutoSent is run (presuming we have the above
menu) just as if you had typed 'SENT', and it quits immediately
afterwards.

Well, try it and I'm sure you will love this little door!
@endnode

@node Requirements "AquaSettings v1.0 Documentation"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
- An Amiga with OS 2.0 or higher.

- AmiExpress, SigmaExpress or any compatible program.
@endnode

@node Installation "AquaSettings v1.0 Documentation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Copy the 'AquaSettings' directory (the inner one) from the archive to your
'Doors:' directory. Then put the provided command icon 'W.info' in your
'BBSCmd' drawer.

The access value in W.info can be set to 1 (the lowest possible) because
the door checks if the user has access to use the internal W command (in
/X 3.0+ determined by the tooltype 'ACS.EDIT_USER_INFO' in the user's
access icon). If he doesn't have access, the door just exits with the
message "Command requires higher access." If you want some users to be
able to use the internal W command but not the other commands that
AquaSettings offer, you can use the tooltype @{"ACCESS" Link Configuration}) to set the access
level below which the door will only run the internal W command.

The door is perfectly safe to be made resident. The changes you have to
make to the command icon in that case are: Change the value of "LOCATION"
to "AquaSettings" and add the tooltype "RESIDENT".

Now, for /X 3.0+, you must put the icon 'W_INTERNAL.info' in your 'BBSCmd'
drawer! The only tooltype it contains is 'INTERNAL=W'. This icon makes it
possible to run the internal W command without quitting the door. Note! It
will NOT work if you put 'W_INTERNAL.info' in 'SYSCmd'!

If you're running SigmaExpress or /X 2.xx you must change the value of the
'DESC.1' tooltype in 'AquaSettings.info' from 'W_INTERNAL' to 'W'. The
side effect is that when you select "[ 1] Basic settings", the door exits
to be able to start the internal W command, so you won't be taken back to
the menu afterwards. (There is no better solution!)

Now you must @{"configure" Link Configuration} the door...
@endnode

@node Configuration "AquaSettings v1.0 Documentation"

Tooltypes in 'Doors:AquaSettings/AquaSettings.info':
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
-  ---  ------ ---------- -------------------------------- ------ ---  --
Template: ACCESS=<access level>                                Optional.
Example : ACCESS=20

If the user has a lower access level than this, only the internal W
command is run. The user won't even notice that a door is installed on W.

-  ---  ------ ---------- -------------------------------- ------ ---  --
Template: CMD.<num>=<command>
Example : CMD.3=CS W

These tooltypes specify all the commands that the users should be able to
start from the AquaSettings menu.

-  ---  ------ ---------- -------------------------------- ------ ---  --
Template: DESC.<num>=<string>
Example : DESC.3=Filescan options

These tooltypes are descriptions for every command. DESC.1 is the
description for CMD.1, DESC.2 is for CMD.2, and so on.

-  ---  ------ ---------- -------------------------------- ------ ---  --
@endnode

